The hydroxyl radical is the most oxidizing ROS and is responsible for the oxidative damage to DNA. The long half-life of the hydroperoxyl radical allows it to reach remote cellular locations. Although the reactivity of the nitric oxide radical is low, its excessive production may lead to cellular damage. It may react with the superoxide radical anion and produce peroxynitrite, which is a powerful oxidizing and nitrating agent, capable of damaging proteins, lipids and DNA (

; 

).

